  "prompt": "Is MSG as bad as usually claimed?",
  "response": "MSG (Monosodium Glutamate) has been the subject of much debate, but current scientific consensus suggests it's generally safe for most people. Here are some key points:\n\n1. Safety:\n- The FDA considers MSG \"generally recognized as safe\" (GRAS)\n- Extensive scientific research has not found consistent evidence of harmful effects\n\n2. \"Chinese Restaurant Syndrome\":\n- Early claims about headaches, nausea, and other symptoms linked to MSG have not been substantiated by rigorous scientific studies\n- Most people can consume MSG without experiencing adverse reactions\n\n3. Naturally Occurring:\n- Glutamate is a naturally occurring amino acid found in many foods like tomatoes, cheese, and mushrooms\n- The human body produces glutamate naturally\n\n4. Potential Sensitivities:\n- A small percentage of people might experience mild, short-term symptoms after consuming large amounts\n- Some individuals might be more sensitive, but this is not common\n\n5. Nutrition:\n- MSG is used as a flavor enhancer, containing sodium and glutamate\n- It does not provide significant nutritional value\n\nWhile individual experiences may vary, scientific evidence does not support claims that MSG is inherently dangerous for most people. As with any food additive, moderation is key.",
